  "response": "Twitter, now known as X, has been the platform for several records, but some of the most notable include:\n\n**Most Retweeted Tweet:**\n\n*   As of 2023, the most retweeted tweet belongs to Japanese billionaire Yusaku Maezawa, who offered to give away money to random people who retweeted his tweet.\n\n**Most Liked Tweet:**\n\n*   The record for the most liked tweet is held by the account for the late Chadwick Boseman, announcing his death from cancer.\n\n**Fastest to a Million Followers:**\n\n*   BTS member Kim Tae-hyung (V) reached 1 million followers in just 43 minutes, the fastest time in Twitter history, when he joined the platform in 2021.\n\n**Most Followers:**\n\n*   As of September 2023, Elon Musk holds the record for the most followers on Twitter, surpassing Barack Obama.\n\n**Most Tweets Per Second (TPS):**\n\n*   A record was set during the 2014 FIFA World Cup semi-final match between Brazil and Germany, peaking at 618,725 tweets per minute or 10,312 tweets per second when Germany scored their 5th goal.\n*   Another significant spike occurred after the release of Hayao Miyazaki's film \"Castle in the Sky\" on Japanese television.  Viewers simultaneously tweeted a magic spell from the movie, creating a TPS of 143,199 in 2013.\n\n**Political Records:**\n\n*   While not a specific record, Barack Obama's victory tweet in 2012 (\"Four more years.\") was one of the most retweeted and liked tweets for a long time.\n\n**Other Notable Mentions:**\n\n*   **First Tweet:** Jack Dorsey's \"just setting up my twttr\" (March 21, 2006).  While not a \"record,\" it's historically significant.\n*   **Rapid Adoption:** Twitter's rapid growth in user base was itself a record in the early days of social media.\n\n**Important Considerations:**\n\n*   **Dynamic Nature:** Records on Twitter are constantly changing, especially in categories like most followers, most liked, and most retweeted. The platform's ever-evolving user base and the nature of viral content mean that these records can be broken relatively quickly.\n*   **Data Accessibility:**  Getting definitive historical data on all Twitter records can be challenging, as Twitter's API and search functionality have changed over time.\n*   **Bots and Authenticity:**  It's important to remember that some follower counts and engagement metrics may be influenced by bots or inauthentic accounts, which can skew the true picture of organic popularity.\n*   **Ownership and Policy Changes:**  Elon Musk's acquisition and the rebranding to \"X\" have led to significant policy and algorithmic changes, which could affect future trends and records on the platform.\n\nTherefore, while the records listed above are accurate to the best of available information, it's important to note that they are subject to change and interpretation.\n",
